      "comment_id" : 106020461,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "An example of using ordinal values safely and correctly can be found here: <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8108980/java-using-enum-with-switch-statement\" title=\"java using enum with switch statement\">stackoverflow.com/questions/8108980/&hellip;</a> Systems like Android limit us to passing int values through native communication mechanisms. When both ends of the communication are in the same application the alignment will not be an issue. So ordinal is a simple and safe solution. But if you have any doubt, assign explicit values as described in the accepted answer by Jon Skeet.  That can never bite you."
